An inmate stands by a window at the Johannesburg Correctional Centre also known as Sun City Prison, South Africa. JOHANNESBURG - Just under 19,000 prisoners will be released on parole as part of efforts to stop the spread of COVID-19 in prisons. President Cyril Ramaphosa has authorised the release of inmates from areas that are at high risk of COVID-19. READ: NGOs call for limited prisoner release The parole only applies to low-risk prisoners who would've applied for parole in the last five years. READ: COVID-19 prison screening launched Parolees will serve the remainder of their sentences under Community Corrections. According to the Presidency, the parole dispensation will apply to low-risk inmates who have passed their minimum detention period or will approach this period in the coming five years. “This dispensation excludes inmates sentenced to life imprisonment or serving terms for specified other serious crimes, including sexual offences, murder and attempted murder, gender-based violence and child abuse.” South Africa has 8,232 confirmed COVID-19 cases with 161 deaths. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.